Call for application: Post-doc position proposal

Field of research: natural language processing, text mining, data 
mining, machine learning

Research project: 3ST (Semantic Highlighter of Scientific Text Corpus)

Supervisors: Fabrice MUHLENBACH and Djamel A. ZIGHED
Starting date / duration: From 1 April 2016 - 12 months

About the project
3ST is an applied research project in which we propose to build semantic 
highlighter of scientific text corpus. With new semantic similarity 
measures between sentences, we seek to identify and highlight parts of 
documents that are semantically and syntactically similar. Through this 
process, information retrieval tasks and search engine indexing for 
scientific corpus become more efficient. In this project we want to 
explore and apply a seemingly promising way which is different from 
other classical approaches (bag of words, statistical weighting methods 
like TF-IDF). This approach consists in using a semantic similarity 
measure between sentences to better capture the meaning of the sentences 
beyond variations in the vocabulary and the syntax of the phrases. Our 
hypothesis is based on the ability to build an accurate semantic 
similarity measure between sentences of a text. Once that model is 
obtained, we will be able to produce a new similarity measure between 
documents that better take into account the semantics. The goal is to 
achieve better information retrieval performance, and finally to build 
new text representation schemes to accelerate the research process.
Our approach, already partially tested on phrases of everyday language, 
has proven to be very encouraging. It consists in: (1) breaking down 
each sentence in a set of semantic part of speech in the form of triples 
(subject, verb, object); (2) using language resources (general or 
specialized ontologies, lexicons and dictionaries) to measure the 
similarities between the same pair of elements contained in a set of 
triples (i.e., subject with subject and verb with verb); (3) identifying 
statistical variables that model the similarity between two sentences 
and (4) aggregating the partial similarities between triples in an 
overall measure between phrases. For the last step of our approach, we 
use supervised learning methods to determine the optimal aggregation 
model; that is to say the one which is closer to human experts.
In this project, we are seeking to explore different variations of the 
four points listed above. We also seek to exploit the available 
collections from the ISTEX platform (http://www.istex.fr/) that aims to 
provide all available means of consultation and analysis now available 
in all scientific communities.
The 3ST project is led by a team from researchers of two university 
laboratories; ERIC laboratory at University Lumière Lyon 2 (venue of the 
candidate) and Hubert Curien Laboratory at the University of Saint-Etienne.

Mission
The candidate will continue the approach developed in the 3ST project, 
benefit from the corpus ISTEX present on the platform and develop a web 
application able to test this approach in the form of a semantic 
highlighter text.

Job description (activities)
The candidate will follow the objectives of the 3ST project and will 
provide theoretical advances in the fields of data mining and machine 
learning, knowledge representation, recommender systems and/or virtual 
communities.
The other kind of scientific developments expected from the candidate 
will be the implementation of a web application. From a query given on 
this web platform (the query consists in one or more target sentences on 
a topic of interest of the user), we expect that the system will return 
a set of papers from the same area of the user and other scientific 
areas. The semantics highlighting system will also help the reader to 
focus on specific parts of the text that are semantically similar to the 
text of the query.

Expected skills
PhD in computer science in the field of natural language processing, 
machine learning or data mining, with strong skills in computer 
development. Knowledge in deep learning will be appreciated. Programming 
languages skills associated with data analysis and mining (R, Python) 
and web development (PHP, MySQL, Java, JavaScript) if possible:
- Fluent English (written, read and spoken), French is not mandatory
- Knowledge in computer language R and Python, Java if possible
- Website development skills (HTML, CSS, PHP, MySQL, JavaScript)
- Interest in deep learning approaches
- Methods and techniques of natural language processing
- Curiosity, come up with new ideas, be very thorough, think out of the box
- Ability to work in teams, ability to listen, understand, and communicate.

Benefits (working conditions):
The position is based in Lyon, France, "Porte des Alpes" campus (Bron).
Salary based on qualifications of the Public Service at the University 
of Lorraine (more than 1800 euros net per month with a possible bonus 
starting from the 6th month).

Additional information (diplomas, schedules, ...): PhD required.
